      <interpGrp xml:id="criticalCommentary_episodes" type="notes">
         <interp xml:id="Bucephalus">Bucephalus, whose name literally means "ox-headed", is named by King Philip because of its wondrous features. According to the prophecy, the indomitable horse can be tamed only by the one who is destined to become king after Philip. In the German corpus, Alexander manages to submit it just with his glare. The name Vestian corresponds to Hephaestion, Alexander's companion and lover, but the medieval tradition doesn't mention the love between the two.</interp>
         <interp xml:id="Alexander_firstBattle">Fifteen-year-old Alexander wants to prove himself worthy of the royal title and asks his father for permission to take up arms. Philip agrees and Alexander goes to fight Nycolaus, an athlete whose figure is here - and in other sources - reinterpreted as the king of Caesarea.</interp>
         <interp xml:id="Alexander_Cleopatra">Alexander reproaches his father for having taken another woman, Cleopatra, and leaving his mother. One of the negative traits of Alexander's character, rage, is here underlined. A brawl ensues, Philip is injured and Alexander calms down. In the V recension, he takes care of his father and reunites his parents, but historical sources tell us that Olympias was repudiated and Alexander was banished after Philip and Cleopatra's wedding till Philip's death.</interp>
         <interp xml:id="Alexander_retakes_city">Alexander subjugates a rebel city, handed down with the corrupted name Antonia in V, which was plotting not to pay tribute to Philip anymore. B does not mention the name of the city, whereas in S this episode is missing.</interp>
         <interp xml:id="tribute_dispute">Much to Alexander's disapproval, Darius's messengers come to collect tribute from Philip. The text anticipates that this dispute will be the cause of Darius's death. From an historical point of view, </interp>
         <interp xml:id="Thelemone"></interp>
      </interpGrp>
    
  
